In less than a week, it‚Äôll be 2020. That‚Äôs absolutely insane.

When I hear 2010, it doesn‚Äôt sound like that long ago, let alone 10 years ago. Even 2015 feels like it just passed us by.

With 2020 fast approaching, a lot of people are going to be setting New Year‚Äôs Resolutions. Setting those goals is amazing, but way too many people are short-sided with them.

If you want to lose *finally* lose weight, don‚Äôt get discouraged when February rolls around and you haven‚Äôt lost weight yet. Your goal isn‚Äôt to lose weight right when 2020 starts- it‚Äôs to lose weight. Period. It might take you a full year to lose a decent amount of weight, but that‚Äôs okay. Imagine where you‚Äôd be right now if you set out to do the same thing on January 1, 2019, and stuck with it?

Waiting a full year to accomplish your goal only feels like a long time until it‚Äôs over. Then suddenly, it flew by.

Whether your goals are health related, business related, or family related, remember that they are not JANUARY resolutions. They‚Äôre 2020 resolutions. That means working towards them for as long as they take.

It pains me to see so many people giving up on their goals. At the end of the day, these are the things that are going to bring us true happiness- isn‚Äôt it worth putting the time in to achieve that?

If you‚Äôre someone who gets discouraged easily, set small goals for yourself instead of one big resolution. Instead of ‚Äúlose weight in 2020‚Äù make a small goal to go to the gym 3 days per week, every week in January. Want to leave your job to start online training? Instead of a resolution to ‚Äúfinally quit your job‚Äù, make a small goal in January to get yourself one client on the side to test the waters. Then build from there.

Make 2020 your year, friends.üçªüßá

Weight training is the gift that keeps on giving, and it goes well beyond simply trying to be muscular. Let‚Äôs dive into a few of the many benefits of weight training.

It seems that people are still absolutely terrified that working with weights is going to make them ‚Äútoo muscular‚Äù. Look, I‚Äôve been trying to be ‚Äútoo muscular‚Äù for 12 years‚Ä¶ you‚Äôre not suddenly going to become a huge monster by lifting some weights. Promise. On the contrary, it‚Äôll give you have that ‚Äúmuscle tone‚Äù *shutters* that so many are after.

From a dieting perspective, weight training is hugely beneficial. Not only will the workouts themselves burn significant calories, but when you increase your overall muscle mass, it increases your caloric needs (aka boosts your metabolism) allowing you to eat more at maintenance. And I don‚Äôt know about you, but eating more is something I can‚Äôt complain about.

The most underrated benefit of weight training is the mental impact. As someone who has long struggled with anxiety, I can say first-hand just how much working out has helped me. Weight training is my therapy, and the boost it gives to my overall mood is something that I value very highly.

What do you find to be the biggest benefit of weight training? Everyone has different reasons for working out, so I‚Äôd love to hear yours!
-

It should never be ‚Äúeat this, not that.‚Äù Eat this sometimes, and eat that other times. Your approach should always be balanced.

If your first thought upon looking at this is ‚Äúthese are all terrible choices,‚Äù then please see yourself out and let us have our edumacation.

Many of us are often looking for lower calorie alternatives to our favorite foods. Like the above, flatbread and low calorie ice cream can be great additions to your diet if you enjoy bagels and ice cream. But they‚Äôre not the ONLY options.

Our diets don‚Äôt need to be all-or-nothing. You don‚Äôt need to give up bagels or ice cream if you love them (who doesn‚Äôt?), but you can choose to opt for an alternative sometimes to save some calories and stay on track if it helps you.

I very much enjoy some of the lower calorie ice cream bars, but you bet your ice cream loving tushie that I‚Äôm going to enjoy a strawberry shortcake bar every once in a while too.

A balanced diet sometimes takes making ‚Äúsacrifices‚Äù to stay on track, but they don‚Äôt need to be sacrifices that make you miserable! Maybe you ‚Äúsacrifice‚Äù the bagel for breakfast and opt for a flatbread instead, then enjoy the Strawberry Shortcake bar at night.

Balance and moderation are your two best friends.

Healthy eating doesn‚Äôt mean that every single food choice you make has to be perfect. Remember to enjoy your food!

One of the first things I recommend to someone starting their health journey: get rid of your scale.

Let‚Äôs be clear. Weighing yourself can be a helpful way to track your progress. And if you have a goal weight, you‚Äôll want to check in on where you are at. But in many cases, the scale becomes way more of a source of stress than a source of useful information.

Obviously if your goal is weight loss, then you hope that your weight is going to go down. But there are 2 problems with that.

The first is that FAT loss and WEIGHT loss are not one and the same. You can lose fat, feel great, but still weigh exactly the same due to your increased muscularity. If you step on the scale and see the number hasn‚Äôt changed, it can be discouraging, when in reality it does not reflect your progress.

The second problem is that your weight is allwwwayyysssss going to fluctuate. While your weight might be trending down over time, your day-to-day weight is going to go up and down. One day you might lose 2 pounds, the next day you might gain 5 pounds. Water retention can make your weight do confusing things overnight, and can be caused by hundreds of different factors that the scale can‚Äôt comprehend.

If you want to weigh yourself to track your progress, go right ahead, but understand that it is only one small measure of progress.

Focus on things like how you feel mentally and physically, how you look, how your clothes fit, if you‚Äôre getting stronger, or how you‚Äôre sleeping.

These are the things that will help define your progress. The scale doesn‚Äôt, and shouldn‚Äôt, tell your story.
-
#fittips #diettips¬†#diethelp #nutrition101 #weightlosstips #weightlosshelp #flexiblediet #fatlosstips #fatlosshelp

Kacey Musgraves said it best: you're damned if you do and you're damned if you don‚Äôt, so you might as well just do whatever you want. When it comes to eating, this is all too true.

We‚Äôve all been there before. We don‚Äôt want a slice of cake at a family party, so we receive countless passive aggressive comments about how we should live a little. Or we DO eat a slice of cake, and someone comments on how we really shouldn‚Äôt be eating sugar.

I‚Äôve been through this, and I know how common it is. If you deal with this, remember that you are far from alone.

Here are some tips I have to help you overcome those comments, but at the end of the day, it‚Äôs something we need to learn to write off. Easier said than done, I know. But people are ALWAYS going to make these comments.

Whether it‚Äôs because that‚Äôs the way they brought up, they‚Äôre insecure about their own choices, or they simply like to judge others‚Ä¶ it‚Äôs always going to happen.

That‚Äôs why it‚Äôs important to stay focused on YOU. Eat what you want. Remember your goals. Commend yourself on your amazing progress. Don‚Äôt worry about what anyone else thinks, because YOU are what matters.

The main thing I want you to remember is that NOBODY actually cares. It feels like they do, and it might feel awkward in the moment, but every single person gets over it almost immediately. If you skipped out on Grandma‚Äôs green bean casserole at Thanksgiving and she questioned you about it, I can guarantee that she has gotten over it.

Confidence is a beautiful thing. Learn to be confident with yourself and your goals, and you‚Äôll be well on your way to telling all those people to screw off. Nicely, if you choose.
-

Whenever I do a Q&A, I get asked how some people can eat whatever they want and never gain weight. So, let‚Äôs explore that.

The answer is quite simple: they are not in a caloric surplus. But there are different ways that might be the case, so let‚Äôs dig in a little further.

The first way is that they‚Äôre just not eating a ton. Sure, they might get McDonald‚Äôs 5 days per week and snack on Oreos throughout the day, but their overall calories might actually be pretty low. While their diet might not be the ‚Äúhealthiest‚Äù, they‚Äôre not over-consuming. Even though it looks like they‚Äôre eating a ton, they‚Äôre actually not from a caloric standpoint.

The second way is that their diet is actually well-rounded, but you‚Äôre just seeing the ‚Äújunk‚Äù. If your coworker is always snacking on cookies and donuts in the office, you might think their diet is garbage. But when they go home, they might actually eat very well. Take it from someone who follows flexible dieting- just because you see someone eating less than optimal food, it doesn‚Äôt mean their whole diet looks like that.

The other ways this might be the case revolve around energy expenditure. Someone might simply have a higher BMR, meaning they require more calories throughout the day. Yes, genetics do play a role to some extent, and someone might naturally have a higher metabolism. But things like age, muscle mass, and even hormones, all play a role in our individual calorie requirements.

Lastly, someone might simply be a very active person. That kid you grew up with that could eat everything in sight was likely also extremely active. I‚Äôve talked about NEAT before: a nurse might eat a lot more than a telemarketer, since they are on the feet all day and therefore burning more calories throughout the day.

At the end of the day, it all comes back to a caloric balance. You can also eat ‚Äúwhatever they want‚Äù and not gain weight if your calories are in check!
-
#fittips #diettips¬†#diethelp #nutrition101 #weightlosstips #weightlosshelp #flexiblediet #macrotracking #macrotracker #flexibledieter

üôã‚Äç‚ôÇÔ∏èWho can relate?

Tracking macros can often feel like a puzzle you‚Äôre constantly trying to solve. Come dinner time, you have to figure out exactly how to fit your food into your daily macros. Or you want dessert, so you need to find the perfect dessert to round out your goals.

Part of me loves solving that puzzle. But another part of me really despises it.

As many of you know, I recently gave up tracking my macros for a month as an experiment. To my surprise, I enjoyed NOT tracking so much that I haven‚Äôt gone back to it. After years and years of meticulously tracking, giving it up felt really, really good.

The biggest relief has been this mental aspect. I never realized just how much time and energy constantly calculating macros required.  I mean, I literally tracked everything I ate, every single day.

Tracking macros provided me with the comfort of knowing I was staying on track, which is great, but it wasn‚Äôt until I gave it up that I realized I didn‚Äôt need that so-called ‚Äúcomfort.‚Äù I lost sight of the mental aspect of it all, and I‚Äôve decided that the mental aspect is far more important to me right now than staying at a specific weight.

I should reiterate that I will still recommend tracking macros to someone trying to reach a weight loss goal. Tracking takes the guesswork out and can really help you hit those goals.

But if you‚Äôre like me and just want to live a healthy life without any specific weight loss goals in mind, not tracking has really freed up my mind and has allowed me to get back to enjoying my waffles to the fullest. üßáüßáüßá
-
#fittips #diettips¬†#diethelp #nutrition101 #weightlosstips #weightlosshelp #flexiblediet #macrotracking #macrotracker #flexibledieter

‚ÄôTis the season of giving. For some people, that means the season of giving people crap about what they eat.

Picture this. You go to a Christmas party with all of your closest friends. Beth recently went on a keto diet and lost 20 pounds, and we‚Äôre very happy for her. Unfortunately, now she has become unbearable to be around and constantly judges anyone who eats sugar.

You grab your favorite Christmas cookie, and Beth emerges from the shadows to tell you that you shouldn‚Äôt be eating all that sugar.

Oh really, Beth? That‚Äôs interesting, I don‚Äôt remember asking you. Let me enjoy my damn Christmas cookies.

I‚Äôve been asked numerous times about Christmas cookies. I know there are lots of them this time of year, but ya know what? It‚Äôs just one time per year! If there‚Äôs a cookie you really love, grab one or two, then walk away and continue on with your party.

Understand that you‚Äôre consuming some extra calories, and that‚Äôs totally fine. Enjoy the cookies you love so much and move on.

There‚Äôs always going to be Beths out there telling you what you should or shouldn‚Äôt eat. Ignore them all. Seriously.

It‚Äôs one thing to want to educate someone, but it‚Äôs another thing to make them feel like crap about their choices. Everyone knows that a cookie isn‚Äôt a health food, and we‚Äôre not grabbing a cookie hoping to lose weight.

Don‚Äôt be a Beth this holiday season.
-

I haven‚Äôt tried the Irish Cream Cold Brew from Starbucks, but was immediately intrigued by the idea, so I decided to make my own today!

The Starbucks version is essentially cold brew with Irish cream flavored syrup, but I wanted to get more creative than that. We‚Äôre going to make our own high-protein Irish cream, froth it into a foam, and pour it over our cold brew!

Here‚Äôs everything you‚Äôll need to make the Irish cream cold foam: - 3/4 Cup Milk of your choice (I highly recommend Silk Protein [it‚Äôs not soy] and based the macros off that)
- 7g Sugar Substitute of choice (I Prefer Swerve)
- 7g @bowmar_nutrition Protein Frosted Cookie (or vanilla Whey)
- 7g @bowmar_nutrition Protein Hot Chocolate (or chocolate whey)
- 1 Tsp Vanilla Extract
- 1/4 Tsp Almond Extract

Combine all of these ingredients and mix well. Use a frother for 30-60 seconds to turn this into a cold foam! If you don‚Äôt have a frother, you can furiously mix in a shaker bottle until it gets foamy.

I only used half of this homemade Irish cream for my drink, but you can use more or less depending on your tastes. The macros above reflect half the recipe.

NOTE: I don‚Äôt like my cold brew overly sweet. If you like a sweeter coffee, you may want to sweeten your cold brew to your usual liking first and THEN top with your Irish cream cold foam, since it doesn‚Äôt add a ton of sweetness throughout on its own.

Enjoy!

NEAT is a very underutilized concept in this industry, so let‚Äôs chat about it.

NEAT stands for non-exercise activity thermogenesis. That‚Äôs just a fancy way of saying that it‚Äôs all the stuff you do that burn calories but aren‚Äôt structured exercise. Walking the dog, pacing on a conference call, cleaning the house, and dancing in the shower are all examples of NEAT.

It‚Äôs no surprise that moving more is beneficial, but let‚Äôs look at why.

If you workout for an hour a day, that only accounts for 4% of your entire day. The rest of your time awake makes up 63% of your day. That‚Äôs 63% of the time you have an opportunity to get some more movement in your life. It‚Äôs no wonder why your NEAT actually accounts for more caloric expenditure than exercise.

NEAT doesn‚Äôt need to be planned. You don‚Äôt need to purposely set aside an hour to take a walk every day. But take some breaks during the work day to walk around the office, or choose the stairs instead of the escalator at the airport. These seemingly small choices can really add up.

If you have an active job where you are on your feet all day, your NEAT is already going to be pretty high. But for a lot of us with desk jobs, it can be easy to go the entire day with very little movement, which is why it is so important to try to get some extra movement in.

The bulk of my NEAT is walking the dog every single day and getting those steps in. What‚Äôs your go-to?

There is no deeper meaning to this comparison‚Ä¶ this is simply to compare the nutritional profiles of these 2 burger options.

I fully understand that you may prefer a plant-based option. Or you may only want to eat meat. Or you may hate fast food and think it‚Äôs all terrible for you. That‚Äôs all fine- I‚Äôm not here to tell you how to eat. And unless you‚Äôve hired someone to tell you how to eat, those decisions should always be up to you.

But I do know that a lot of people out there assume that the plant-based option is automatically healthier from a nutritional standpoint, so I want to share this comparison to show you that may or may not be true.

Nutritionally, these options are incredibly similar, and neither stands out as a clear-cut ‚Äúbetter‚Äù option. Since the sandwiches are built exactly the same in terms of bun and condiments, you can see that the Impossible Burger patty has 30 less calories, 6g less fat, 3g less protein, and 9g more carbs.

The one thing I will add that isn‚Äôt evident in this comparison is that plant-based meat is very heavily processed. If processed food is something you deem unhealthy (which according to recent comments, a lot of people do) then you may want to think twice before picking up an Impossible Burger.

All that being said, have you had an Impossible Burger? Either at Burger King or elsewhere? I‚Äôve tried it once and did not really enjoy it, but am willing to give it another shot.

When I first came across Justin‚Äôs Peanut Butter Cups years ago, I grabbed them immediately. Reese‚Äôs are without a doubt my favorite candy, so when a so-called healthier version rolled around, I jumped all over it.

It wasn‚Äôt until years later, when I gained a true understanding of nutrition and macronutrients, that I realized they‚Äôre really not much different than my beloved Reese‚Äôs.

At that time, I was hyper-focused on eating ‚Äúclean‚Äù. I always figured that eating candy was a horrible choice, especially if you wanted to lose weight.

But an ORGANIC candy? That‚Äôs totally different. I assumed that meant I could enjoy my candy guilt-free. Spoiler alert- you can enjoy ANY food guilt-free.

At the end of the day, these products have very similar ingredients. One has peanuts, the other has organic peanuts. One has sugar, the other has organic sugar. One has soy lecithin, the other has organic soy lecithin.

Macronutrient-wise, they‚Äôre also very similar. Either choice is going to be roughly the same calories, fat, carbs, and protein, with some slight differences.

I‚Äôm not bashing organic eating. If you prefer organic products, you have every right. And to be totally honest, the Justin‚Äôs Peanut Butter Cups taste awesome, too.

But don‚Äôt blindly assume that the organic option is automatically the ‚Äúbetter‚Äù choice. Organic candy is still candy.

If you love Reese‚Äôs, you should be able to enjoy one without any guilt or fear. Being flexible with your diet means enjoying ANY food you love in moderation- even candy.
-
#fittips #diettips¬†#diethelp #nutrition101 #weightlosstips #weightlosshelp #flexiblediet #fatlosstips

You don‚Äôt need a new year to start chasing your goals.

The new year is always a time when people set goals for themselves. It makes sense, too. I mean, the calendar resets, so why not make this YOUR year?

But you don‚Äôt need a calendar to tell you when to start. You can do it right now.

Whether you have goals revolving around weight loss, strength gains, business, or relationships, you can start today. Or tomorrow. Or this weekend. You don‚Äôt need to wait until January 1.

Weight loss goals are very common when the new year rolls around. The problem with these goals, in most cases, is that people try to achieve quick results. They start January 1st and hope that they‚Äôll be 20 pounds down by February. But like most things in life, those results take time.

Let‚Äôs say that realistically, you lose 1 pound per week. That doesn‚Äôt sound like much, but it is certainly attainable. If you start right now, you‚Äôll have a 4 pound jump on your weight loss goal come January 1st. By February, you‚Äôll be down 8 pounds. That is not only a realistic goal, but amazing progress.

Whatever goals you have set for yourself, I urge you to consider starting them now.

2020 is going to be your year, and you‚Äôre going to crush your goals. ESPECIALLY if you get a head start on them. ‚ÄúThe¬†best time to plant a tree¬†was 20 years ago. The second¬†best time¬†is now.‚Äù Not 4 weeks from now. Right. Now.
-
#fittips #diettips¬†#diethelp #fitnessgoals #weightlosstips #weightlosshelp #2020resolution #fatlosstips #weightlossgoal

Too many calories, even if it‚Äôs from the healthiest foods in the world, is still too many calories.

A very common desire for people is to build muscle with very little fat gain. It‚Äôs a valid desire. However, in that pursuit, I often see people trying to do what they consider ‚Äúclean bulking‚Äù, or just eating a ton of healthy food.

They know that you need to be in a caloric surplus to build muscle, so they assume that if the surplus is all ‚Äúgood‚Äù food, then they‚Äôll only add ‚Äúgood‚Äù weight. But it doesn‚Äôt work like that.

If your body needs 2500 daily calories, and you eat 5000 calories worth of nothing but chicken, rice, and salad every day, you‚Äôre still going to gain fat. While it‚Äôs great to prioritize healthier options, too many calories is still going to put you in too large of a caloric surplus, which is what is going to lead to fat gain.

Think about it this way- if you want to lose weight and you drastically cut your calories, you‚Äôre not going to see the results you want. Yes you‚Äôll lose weight, but you‚Äôll also lose hard-earned muscle and the results will not be sustainable.

Instead, you‚Äôd want to slowly decrease your calories over time to reach sustainable, realistic results. Building muscle works the same way.

You can drastically increase your calories suddenly, and you‚Äôll build muscle (assuming you are working out, of course) but you‚Äôll also add unwanted fat. If you want to minimize the fat gain, you need to slowly increase your calories over time.

By keeping your caloric surplus minimal, it will allow you to build muscle without adding a buttload of fat. And yes, you can even include a cookie or twelve in the process.

If building muscle is your ultimate goal, please understand that some fat gain is part of that process and inevitable. Embrace it, it means you‚Äôre growing! But using this approach, you can keep it to a minimum.
-
#fittips #diettips¬†#diethelp #nutrition101 #weightlosstips #weightlosshelp #flexiblediet #cleanbulk #bulkingseason

Eating an extra couple hundred calories should never be a big deal, but it certainly feels that way to many out there.

When you‚Äôre counting calories, it‚Äôs easy to overthink things. If you want to eat 2000 calories but end up at 2200 calories, it‚Äôs easy to stress about it.

There are a lot of layers to why you shouldn‚Äôt stress about a few hundred extra calories, but let‚Äôs tackle it at face value. Let‚Äôs pretend you ate a donut today and it put you over your goal by 200 calories, which bums you out. Before anyone yells at me that donuts are more than 200 calories, a glazed Krispy Kreme donut is 200 calories. Look it up.

Now on the flip side, let‚Äôs say you hit your 2000 calorie goal perfectly. But it was also a crazy day at work which had you moving around a ton, leading to an extra 4000 steps. We‚Äôll estimate and say that burned about 200 extra calories for the day.

Just as easily as you went over your goal by 200 calories one day, you were under your goal by 200 calories another day. One situation stressed you out, and the other you probably didn‚Äôt even realize.

What‚Äôs the point here?

Don‚Äôt stress about hitting your calories perfectly. Perfection in nutrition doesn‚Äôt exist.

There are SO many factors at play that affect how many calories you are burning. On any given day, you may very well burn a few hundred calories more or less.

So don‚Äôt stress if you eat a few hundred calories more or less.

It will all balance out, I promise.
-

If you‚Äôve fallen in love with working out, it can be really difficult to take an extended break. You can enjoy a few rest days, but a full week feels like a death sentence. I‚Äôm here to tell you that it is actually really, really good for you.
